Actions by Justice Department officials in spying on a Donald Trump campaign adviser in 2016 could be a crime or merely an administrative offense, legal experts say.
Barr also indicated that he planned a further review of government “spying” on the Trump campaign.
“Before looking at the legality, the department should examine the process behind getting a FISA warrant against a presidential campaign.
That’s something that should be approved by the attorney general first,” John Yoo, a former assistant U.S. attorney general under President George W. Bush, told The Daily Signal.
… There was a lot of justifiable investigative activity into the campaign and campaign officials and their relationship with Russia and the Russian government.